\begin{IDEA}
**Title: The Moderating Role of Organizational Enablers in AI-Driven Role Evolution**

This study develops a typology of employee experiences by clustering respondents into "Augmented" (high creative/complex task growth) and "Displaced" (high repetitive task growth) profiles using the `QGP` and `QGU` indices. By controlling for industry (`QDB`) and job profile (`HIDDG`) to isolate role-specific baseline dynamics, the analysis evaluates whether perceived job security (`QEA_2`, `QEB_2`) is driven by individual AI usage frequency (`QC`) or by the presence of structural organizational support. The core objective is to test if high-scoring `QKB` (company enablers) and `QGO` (culture) variables act as significant moderators that decouple high AI integration from job insecurity. Utilizing a Random Forest permutation importance framework and mediation analysis, the research distinguishes between "anxiety-driven" AI adoption and "growth-driven" adoption. This approach shifts the focus from simple usage correlations to identifying the specific organizational configurations that successfully transition employees from task displacement to professional augmentation.
\end{IDEA}


