\begin{IDEA}
**Title: Quantifying Sentiment Volatility: Determinants of the Delta between Current and Future AI-Driven Job Security**

This study shifts the focus from static sentiment clustering to the analysis of "Security Volatility"—the numerical delta between current (`QEA_2`) and 3-year expected (`QEB_2`) job security perceptions. By treating the transition from current to future sentiment as the dependent variable, the research isolates the factors that stabilize or destabilize employee outlooks amid AI integration. Using OLS regression and Random Forest permutation importance, we evaluate the predictive power of specific organizational enablers (`QKB`) and cultural markers (`QGO`) in narrowing the gap between current anxiety and future professional optimism. To mitigate endogeneity, the model controls for individual "AI-Sentiment" profiles—derived from the binary `QHD` emotional attitude block—to isolate structural policy influence from baseline cognitive bias. The objective is to identify which specific company interventions, such as "employee involvement in development" (QKB_1_11) or "regular training" (QKB_1_4), serve as the strongest predictors of positive sentiment trajectory across distinct job profiles (`HIDDG`) and sectors (`QDB`). This approach moves beyond descriptive sentiment analysis to identify actionable organizational configurations that foster long-term job confidence.
\end{IDEA}


